THE ARMADILLo, oa TATU.

This little animal, which is scarce larger than* a common tortoise, is called by the Spaniards- armadillo. Its whole body is armed with horny scales, elegantly varied with red and white. Its- head, which resembles that of a young pigf it discovers in walking, but on the approach of¹ danger entirely conceals under this coat of mail. It has rather a long neck. Its scales are clothed here and there with white haim, especially under the belly. The feet are like those of a tortoise‚ with five unequal fingers, armed with very sharp nails with which it digs holes under ground to hide itself in, or clings so firmly to the surface of the earth that the strongest man can hardly make it loosen its hold. It has a long scaly tail, of which, prefixed to a reed, the Abipones make military trumpets. Its little· ears are destitute both of hairs and scaleS.
